<!-- ++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++
  Schema: Probability_arm
   <express_ref linkend="probability:arm:Probability_arm"/>
  ++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++ -->

<ext_description linkend="Probability_arm">
The probability UoF specifies the information needed to specify a value of a probability together with any parameter values used to derive it from a probability distribution.
</ext_description>

<!-- 
  ++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++
   Schema: Probability_arm  Type: probability_class_item 
   <express_ref linkend="probability:arm:Probability_arm.probability_class_item"/>
  ++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++ 
  -->
<ext_description linkend="Probability_arm.probability_class_item">
The <b>probability_class_item</b> type is an extension of the <b>classification_item</b> type. 
It adds to this latter type the entity data type <b>Probability_by_class</b>.
</ext_description>
<!-- 
  ++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++
   Schema: Probability_arm  Type: probability_derivation 
   <express_ref linkend="probability:arm:Probability_arm.probability_derivation"/>
  ++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++ 
  -->
<ext_description linkend="Probability_arm.probability_derivation">
<b>Probability_derivation</b> links the <b>Probability_numeric.value</b> to the <b>Probability_distribution</b> it derives from and the <b>parmaters</b> used to derive
the value.
<example> A probability of "0.67" is derived from a Normal (or Gaussian) distribution using the parameter "plus or minus '1.0' standard deviations from the mean" </example>
</ext_description>

<!-- 
  ++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++
   Schema: Probability_arm  Type: probability_item 
   <express_ref linkend="probability:arm:Probability_arm.probability_item"/>
  ++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++ 
  -->
<ext_description linkend="Probability_arm.probability_item">
</ext_description>

<!-- 
  ++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++
   Schema: Probability_arm  Entity: Parameter  
   <express_ref linkend="probability:arm:Probability_arm.Parameter"/>
  ++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++ 
  -->
<ext_description linkend="Probability_arm.Parameter">
A parameter is a value used by a <b>Probability_derivation</b> in a particular role in
order to calculate the particular probability.
<example> In a coin tossing trial, the probability calculated is that of getting more than 6 heads
in ten tosses. The parameter with the role "at least [parameter_value] heads" will have the
value "6" </example>
</ext_description>
<!-- 
  ++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++
   Schema: Probability_arm  Entity: Parameter  Attribute: parameter_role 
   <express_ref linkend="probability:arm:Probability_arm.Parameter.parameter_role"/>
  ++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++ 
  -->
<ext_description linkend="Probability_arm.Parameter.parameter_role">
<b>Parameter_role</b> identifies how the parameter is used in calculating the particular 
probability value.
<note> The set of roles and their interpretation is defined through reference data.</note>
</ext_description>

<!-- 
  ++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++
   Schema: Probability_arm  Entity: Parameter  Attribute: parameter_value 
   <express_ref linkend="probability:arm:Probability_arm.Parameter.parameter_value"/>
  ++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++ 
  -->
<ext_description linkend="Probability_arm.Parameter.parameter_value">
The value to be applied when using the <b>Parameter</b>
</ext_description>

<!-- 
  ++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++
   Schema: Probability_arm  Entity: Probability  
   <express_ref linkend="probability:arm:Probability_arm.Probability"/>
  ++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++ 
  -->
<ext_description linkend="Probability_arm.Probability">
<b>Probability</b> represents the general concept of probability.
</ext_description>
<!-- 
  ++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++
   Schema: Probability_arm  Entity: Probability_association  
   <express_ref linkend="probability:arm:Probability_arm.Probability_association"/>
  ++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++ 
  -->
<ext_description linkend="Probability_arm.Probability_association">
<b>Probability_association</b> allows a particular probability to be applied.
<example> A <b>Probability</b> of 0.5 can be associated with the event "a coin lands heads up".</example>
<example> A <b>Probability</b> of 0.01 can be associated with the state "equipment has failed". </example>
</ext_description>

<!-- 
  ++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++
   Schema: Probability_arm  Entity: Probability_association  Attribute: applies_to 
   <express_ref linkend="probability:arm:Probability_arm.Probability_association.applies_to"/>
  ++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++ 
  -->
<ext_description linkend="Probability_arm.Probability_association.applies_to">
The entity which the <b>Probability</b> applies to, defined though the extensible select <b>probability_item</b>
</ext_description>

<!-- 
  ++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++
   Schema: Probability_arm  Entity: Probability_association  Attribute: has_probability 
   <express_ref linkend="probability:arm:Probability_arm.Probability_association.has_probability"/>
  ++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++ 
  -->
<ext_description linkend="Probability_arm.Probability_association.has_probability">
The <b>Probability</b> that applies to the associated entity.
</ext_description>
<!-- 
  ++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++
   Schema: Probability_arm  Entity: Probability_by_class  
   <express_ref linkend="probability:arm:Probability_arm.Probability_by_class"/>
  ++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++ 
  -->
<ext_description linkend="Probability_arm.Probability_by_class">
<b>Probability_by_class</b> allows the value of probability to be one of a set of named classes of probability
rather than assigning a specific numerical value, which may not be available.
<example> A safety assessment methodology classes the probability an accident as "very unlikely", "unlikely", "significantly likely" and
"almost certain". Any process that has a "very likely" or "almost certain" chance of causing serious injury is shut down. </example>
</ext_description>

<!-- 
  ++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++
   Schema: Probability_arm  Entity: Probability_derivation  
   <express_ref linkend="probability:arm:Probability_arm.Probability_derivation"/>
  ++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++ 
  -->
<ext_description linkend="Probability_arm.Probability_derivation">
A <b>Probability_derivation</b> associates a particular value of <b>Probability</b>
with the probability distribution used to calculate it and the parameters used to 
get the particular value.
<note> The parameters of <b>Probability_derivation</b> are those needed to get a single value from
the distibution, and not those which characterise the distribution. For example, in the case of coin tossing,
the distribution is a Binomial distribution, with parameters of probability for a single toss, and
number of tosses, whereas the parameter for the <b>Probability_derivation</b> will be the number of heads
obtained. </note> 
</ext_description>

<!-- 
  ++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++
   Schema: Probability_arm  Entity: Probability_derivation  Attribute: derives_from 
   <express_ref linkend="probability:arm:Probability_arm.Probability_derivation.derives_from"/>
  ++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++ 
  -->
<ext_description linkend="Probability_arm.Probability_derivation.derives_from">
The <b>Probability_distribution</b> that is the basis for the probability value.
</ext_description>

<!-- 
  ++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++
   Schema: Probability_arm  Entity: Probability_derivation  Attribute: gives_value 
   <express_ref linkend="probability:arm:Probability_arm.Probability_derivation.gives_value"/>
  ++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++ 
  -->
<ext_description linkend="Probability_arm.Probability_derivation.gives_value">
The <b>Probability</b> which results from the <b>Probability_derivation</b>.
</ext_description>

<!-- 
  ++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++
   Schema: Probability_arm  Entity: Probability_derivation  Attribute: has_parameter 
   <express_ref linkend="probability:arm:Probability_arm.Probability_derivation.has_parameter"/>
  ++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++ 
  -->
<ext_description linkend="Probability_arm.Probability_derivation.has_parameter">
The set of parameters which are applied to the <b>Probability_distribution</b> to get the actual <b>Probability.value</b>.
</ext_description>

